  "source": "Pediatrics_Nelson_textbook_data.txt - Minimal change disease (MCD) is the most common cause of nephrotic syndrome in children, accounting for approximately 80% of cases in children under age 10 years. The characteristic pathologic finding is the absence of abnormalities on light microscopy ('minimal change'), negative immunofluorescence, and diffuse effacement of podocyte foot processes on electron microscopy. Clinical features include the sudden onset of edema, massive proteinuria (often >50 mg/kg/day), hypoalbuminemia (<2.5 g/dL), and hypercholesterolemia. Most children have normal blood pressure and normal renal function. The etiology is unknown, but it is thought to involve T-cell dysfunction leading to the production of a circulating factor that damages podocytes. Corticosteroids are the cornerstone of treatment, with prednisone or prednisolone typically administered at a dose of 60 mg/m²/day (maximum 60 mg/day) for 4-6 weeks, followed by 40 mg/m²/alternate days for another 4-6 weeks with subsequent tapering. Approximately 90% of children with MCD achieve complete remission with this regimen, with most showing a response within 2 weeks. For frequent relapses or steroid-dependent disease, alternative therapies include cyclophosphamide, cyclosporine, tacrolimus, mycophenolate mofetil, or rituximab. The long-term prognosis is excellent, with most children eventually achieving permanent remission and normal kidney function.",
  "category": "Pediatrics"
