  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - Nephrotic syndrome in adults requires a systematic approach to diagnosis, with renal biopsy playing a central role in identifying the underlying pathology. Common causes in adults include primary glomerular diseases (membranous nephropathy, focal segmental glomerulosclerosis, minimal change disease) and secondary causes (diabetes, lupus, amyloidosis, medications). Drug-induced nephrotic syndrome is an important consideration, with nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) being a well-recognized cause. NSAIDs can lead to nephrotic syndrome through several mechanisms, including minimal change disease, acute interstitial nephritis with nephrotic-range proteinuria, and rarely membranous nephropathy. The nephrotoxicity of NSAIDs is dose-dependent and related to their inhibition of renal prostaglandins, which regulate renal hemodynamics and salt and water homeostasis. In patients with heavy proteinuria (>3.5 g/day) and nephrotic syndrome, renal biopsy is generally indicated to establish the specific diagnosis, guide therapy, and provide prognostic information. This is particularly important in adults, where the spectrum of diseases causing nephrotic syndrome is broader than in children, and the likelihood of minimal change disease (which has an excellent response to corticosteroids) is much lower. While drug discontinuation may lead to improvement in some cases of NSAID-induced nephropathy, definitive diagnosis through biopsy is often necessary before initiating specific therapies, particularly in cases with significant proteinuria, renal dysfunction, or systemic symptoms.",
