  "source": "Obstentrics_Williams_textbook_data.txt - Preeclampsia is a multisystem disorder characterized by new-onset hypertension and proteinuria or end-organ dysfunction after 20 weeks of gestation. Severe features include systolic blood pressure ≥160 mm Hg or diastolic blood pressure ≥110 mm Hg, thrombocytopenia (<100,000/μL), impaired liver function (elevated transaminases to twice normal concentration), progressive renal insufficiency, pulmonary edema, or new-onset cerebral or visual disturbances. When preeclampsia is diagnosed, the decision for delivery depends on gestational age, maternal and fetal condition, and severity of disease. For pregnancies <34 weeks with severe preeclampsia, a short delay (24-48 hours) may be considered to administer corticosteroids for fetal lung maturity if the maternal and fetal conditions are stable. However, immediate delivery is indicated regardless of gestational age if there is maternal hemodynamic instability, eclampsia, pulmonary edema, disseminated intravascular coagulation, abruptio placentae, or non-reassuring fetal testing. For gestations ≥34 weeks with severe preeclampsia, delivery is recommended. Magnesium sulfate is administered for seizure prophylaxis in severe preeclampsia, continuing through delivery and for at least 24 hours postpartum. Antihypertensive therapy is generally initiated for persistent systolic blood pressure ≥160 mm Hg or diastolic blood pressure ≥110 mm Hg to prevent maternal cerebrovascular accidents and congestive heart failure.",
