  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt - HIV-associated nephropathy (HIVAN) is a distinctive form of kidney disease characterized by heavy proteinuria, often in the nephrotic range, and rapidly progressive renal failure. The most common histopathologic finding is collapsing focal segmental glomerulosclerosis (FSGS), though other patterns may also be observed. HIVAN predominantly affects individuals of African descent, suggesting a genetic predisposition, and is associated with advanced HIV disease, though it can occur at any CD4 count. Risk factors include intravenous drug use, untreated HIV infection, and genetic variants in APOL1. Clinical presentation typically includes nephrotic-range proteinuria (often >3.5 g/day), hypoalbuminemia, edema, and variable degrees of renal insufficiency. Urinalysis shows significant proteinuria with minimal hematuria, and renal ultrasound often reveals enlarged, echogenic kidneys. The diagnosis is established by demonstrating HIV infection in a patient with compatible clinical and laboratory findings, though renal biopsy provides definitive diagnosis. The mainstay of treatment is antiretroviral therapy (ART), which can slow or halt disease progression and may even lead to partial reversal of renal dysfunction if initiated early. Adjunctive therapies include ACE inhibitors or ARBs for proteinuria reduction, and corticosteroids in select cases. Without treatment, HIVAN typically progresses to end-stage renal disease within months.",
